
Objectives
By the end of this lab, you will be able to:

Understand different volume types in containerization
Create and manage named volumes
Implement bind mounts with proper SELinux context (:Z option)
Configure host directory permissions for container access
Verify data persistence across container lifecycles
Prerequisites
Podman installed (version 3.0+ recommended)
Basic Linux command line knowledge
SELinux enabled system (default on RHEL-based systems)
sudo privileges for certain operations
Lab Setup
Ensure Podman is installed:
sudo dnf install podman
Verify installation:
podman --version
Task 1: Creating and Using Named Volumes
Subtask 1.1: Create a Named Volume
podman volume create mydata_volume
Explanation:
This creates a persistent storage volume managed by Podman.

Verification:

podman volume ls
Expected Output:

DRIVER      VOLUME NAME
local       mydata_volume
Subtask 1.2: Use the Volume in a Container
podman run -d --name volume_test -v mydata_volume:/data docker.io/library/alpine sleep infinity
Explanation:
This runs an Alpine container with the volume mounted at /data.

Verification:

podman exec volume_test ls /data
(No output expected as the directory is empty)

Subtask 1.3: Test Data Persistence
podman exec volume_test sh -c "echo 'Persistent Data' > /data/testfile"
podman stop volume_test
podman rm volume_test
podman run --name new_test -v mydata_volume:/data docker.io/library/alpine cat /data/testfile
Expected Output:

Persistent Data
Task 2: Bind Mounts with SELinux Context
Subtask 2.1: Create Host Directory
mkdir ~/container_data
echo "Host file content" > ~/container_data/hostfile.txt
Subtask 2.2: Mount with :Z Option
podman run -it --rm -v ~/container_data:/container_data:Z docker.io/library/alpine cat /container_data/hostfile.txt
Explanation:
The :Z option tells SELinux to relabel the content for container access.

Expected Output:

Host file content
Subtask 2.3: Verify SELinux Context
ls -Z ~/container_data/hostfile.txt
Expected Output:

unconfined_u:object_r:container_file_t:s0 /home/user/container_data/hostfile.txt
Task 3: Adjusting Host Directory Permissions
Subtask 3.1: Create Restricted Directory
sudo mkdir /restricted_data
sudo chmod 700 /restricted_data
sudo chown root:root /restricted_data
Subtask 3.2: Test Access Without Adjustments
podman run -it --rm -v /restricted_data:/data docker.io/library/alpine touch /data/testfile
Expected Outcome: Permission denied error

Subtask 3.3: Fix Permissions and SELinux
sudo chmod 755 /restricted_data
sudo chcon -t container_file_t /restricted_data
podman run -it --rm -v /restricted_data:/data:Z docker.io/library/alpine touch /data/testfile
Verification:

ls -lZ /restricted_data
Should show the new file with correct context

Task 4: Comprehensive Data Persistence Test
Subtask 4.1: Create Test Environment
podman run -d --name persist_test -v mydata_volume:/data -v ~/container_data:/container_data:Z docker.io/library/alpine sleep infinity
Subtask 4.2: Write Test Data
podman exec persist_test sh -c "echo 'Named Volume Data' >> /data/named.txt"
podman exec persist_test sh -c "echo 'Bind Mount Data' >> /container_data/bind.txt"
Subtask 4.3: Verify Persistence
podman stop persist_test
podman rm persist_test
podman run --rm -v mydata_volume:/data docker.io/library/alpine cat /data/named.txt
cat ~/container_data/bind.txt
Expected Output:

Named Volume Data
Bind Mount Data
Troubleshooting Tips
If getting permission errors:

Ensure SELinux is in enforcing mode (getenforce)
Use :Z for bind mounts
Check directory permissions (ls -lZ)
Volume not persisting:

Verify volume exists (podman volume ls)
Check mount point in container (podman inspect <container>)
SELinux issues:

Check audit logs (sudo ausearch -m avc -ts recent)
Consider temporary permissive mode for testing (sudo setenforce 0)
